ref: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.12, p.1575 (1975)
title: Transfer Reactions With Heavy Ions On Light Nuclei

x4freetext: TRANSFER REACTIONS WITH HEAVY IONS ON LIGHT NUCLEI

x4codes.hlp: Texas A & M University, College Station, TX, United States of America

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.12, p.1575 (1975)

x4codes.hlp: Texas A & M University, College Station, TX, United States of America

x4freetext: 50 MICROMETERS SOLST FOR DET1,
50 MICROMETERS SOLST FOR DET2, AND 2000 MICROMETERS
SOLST FOR DET3 ARE TYPICAL THICKNESS.
430 MICROGRAMS PER SQUARE CENTIMETERS NATURAL CARBON
FOILS WERE USED.
THE ANALYZED BEAM HAD AN ESTIMATED ENERGY
UNCERTAINTY OF +-0.5 PERCENT.
THE EXPERIMENTAL ENERGY RESOLUTION WAS IN THE RANGE
OF 600-900 KEV, MAINLY DUE TO KINEMATIC BROADENING.
THE UNCERTAINTIES IN ENERGY CALIBRATION OF PEAK IN
SPECTRUM WERE ABOUT 100 KEV AT LOW EXCITATION
ENERGIES.
THE ESTIMATED ERRORS IN ABSOLUTE CROSS SECTIONS
WERE ABOUT 20 PERCENT DUE TO THE UNCERTAINTIES
IN TARGET THICKNESS MEASUREMENTS, CHARGE COLLECTION
IN THE FARADAY CUP, ETC.(AUTHORS)
THE STATISTICAL ERRORS ESTIMATED FROM THE SIZES OF
DATA POINTS WERE SMALLER THAN 8 PERCENT.(COMPILER)

RESPECTIVELY.

UNCERTAINTY OF +-0.5 PERCENT.
THE EXPERIMENTAL ENERGY RESOLUTION WAS IN THE RANGE
OF 600-900 KEV, MAINLY DUE TO KINEMATIC BROADENING.

SPECTRUM WERE ABOUT 100 KEV AT LOW EXCITATION
ENERGIES.

WERE ABOUT 20 PERCENT DUE TO THE UNCERTAINTIES
IN TARGET THICKNESS MEASUREMENTS, CHARGE COLLECTION
